"Álvarez M., Gourcuff C.","Uncoupled transport of chlorofluorocarbons and anthropogenic carbon in the subpolar North Atlantic",2010,"Deep-Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers","57","7",,"860","868",,,10.1016/j.dsr.2010.03.009,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77954864085&partnerID=40&md5=fdc365d3ffe3275b0a09eb162c4d46c5","IMEDEA (CSIC-UIB), Miquel Marqués 21, 07190 Esporles, Spain; CNES, Ifremer, Plouzanè, France","Álvarez, M., IMEDEA (CSIC-UIB), Miquel Marqués 21, 07190 Esporles, Spain; Gourcuff, C., CNES, Ifremer, Plouzanè, France","Chlorofluorocarbon (CFC) 11 and 12 transports across the transoceanic World Ocean Circulation Experiment (WOCE) A25 section in the subpolar North Atlantic are derived from an inverse model using hydrographic and ADCP data (Lherminier et al., 2007). CFC and anthropogenic carbon (C ANT) advective transports contrary to expected are uncoupled: C ANT is transported northeastwards (82±39kmols -1) mainly within the overturning circulation, while CFC-11 and CFC-12 are transported southwestwards (-24±4 and -11±2mols -1, respectively) as part of the large-scale horizontal circulation. The main reason for this uncoupled behaviour is the complex CFC vs. C ANT relation in the ocean, which stems from the contrasting temperature relation for both tracers: more C ANT dissolves in warmer waters with a low Revelle factor, while CFC's solubility is higher in cold waters. These results point to C ANT and CFC having different routes of uptake, accumulation and transport within the ocean, and hence: C ANT transport would be more sensitive to changes in the overturning circulation strength, while CFC to changes in the East Greenland Current and Labrador Sea Water formation in the Irminger Sea. Additionally, C ANT and CFCs would have different sensitivities to circulation and climate changes derived from global warming as the slowdown of the overturning circulation, increase stratification due to warming and changes in wind stress. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.","Advective transports; Anthropogenic carbon; CFC; Subpolar North Atlantic","Advective transport; Anthropogenic carbon; Cold waters; East greenland currents; Inverse models; Labrador sea waters; North Atlantic; Overturning circulation; World Ocean Circulation Experiment; Chlorofluorocarbons; Global warming; Ocean currents; Transportation routes; advection; air-sea interaction; anthropogenic source; bioaccumulation; CFC; climate change; hydrographic survey; overturn; wind stress; Arctic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (North); East Greenland Current",,,,,,"Álvarez, M., Ríos, A.F., Pérez, F.F., Bryden, H.L., Rosón, G., Transports and budgets of total inorganic carbon in the Subpolar and Temperate North Atlantic (2003) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 17 (1), p. 1002; Álvarez, M., Pérez, F.F., Bryden, H., Ríos, A.F., Physical and biogeochemical transports structure in the North Atlantic subpolar gyre (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. C03027; Álvarez, M., Bryden, H.L., Pérez, F.F., Ríos, A.F., Rosón, G., Physical and biogeochemical fluxes and net budgets in the Subpolar and Temperate North Atlantic (2002) J. Mar. Res., 60, pp. 191-226; Anderson, L.A., Sarmiento, J.L., Redfield ratios of remineralization determined by nutrient data analysis (1994) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 8, pp. 65-80; Bacon, S., (1998) Two hydrographic sections across the boundaries of the Subpolar Gyre: FOUREX., 16, p. 104. , RRS Discovery cruise 230, 07 Aug.-17 Sep. 1997, Southampton Oceanography Centre Cruise Report; Boswell, S.M., Smythe-Wright, D., Dual-detector system for the shipboard analysis of halocarbons in sea-water and air for oceanographic tracer studies (1996) Analyst, 121, pp. 505-509; Broecker, W.S., Takahashi, T., Simpson, H.J., Peng, T.H., Fate of fossil fuel carbon dioxide and the global carbon budget (1979) Science, 206, pp. 409-418; Bullister, J.L., Weiss, R.F., Determination of CC13F and CC12F2 seawater and air (1988) Deep-Sea Res., 25, pp. 839-853; Du